## Core Principles

### Performance & Simplicity First (ПРИОРИТЕТ №1)
**RULE: Performance and simplicity have the highest priority.**
**RULE: Always prefer the simplest possible solution that meets the requirements.**
**RULE: Do NOT add abstractions, libraries, or logic unless explicitly required.**

See `cursor/rules/performance_minimalism.mdc` for detailed performance and minimalism rules.

### Reliability First
**Главный приоритет:** Создание надежного и стабильного сайта. Качество важнее скорости.

### WordPress Best Practices
- Follow WordPress Coding Standards
- Use WordPress functions and hooks
- Security first: always escape and sanitize data
- Content management through CMS (no hardcoded content)

### Content Separation
- All dynamic content managed through WordPress Admin Panel
- Portfolio items, testimonials, services, contacts - everything editable
- Administrator should be able to change everything without touching code

## Responsibilities

- After writing or editing code:
  - Automatically check for syntax and lexical errors
  - Ensure new code does not break existing functionality or logic
  - Verify WordPress compatibility and best practices
  - Check that content is managed through CMS, not hardcoded
  - Automatically fix detected issues and apply improvements
  - Maintain semantic structure in HTML and accessibility (a11y) where relevant
  - Refactor repetitious or verbose code (DRY, KISS, YAGNI)
  - Add clear, English-language comments when code is non-obvious
  - Test WordPress integration (SCF fields, custom post types)

- WordPress-specific checks:
  - All user data properly escaped (esc_html, esc_attr, esc_url)
  - Proper use of wp_enqueue_script/style
  - Check SCF field existence before output
  - Follow WordPress template hierarchy
  - Use WordPress functions instead of custom solutions where possible

- Use the "plan → act" workflow:
  - Present a plan of action first
  - Execute only after confirmation
  - Show what was changed and why
  - Document WordPress integration points

## Code Quality Standards

- **Reliability:** Code must work consistently, handle edge cases
- **Security:** WordPress security best practices mandatory
- **Performance:** Optimize assets, use lazy loading, minimize queries
- **Maintainability:** Clean, readable, well-documented code
- **Scalability:** Easy to add new features and content types
